=== 2.3 Matrix Multiplication

Given a matrix stem:[A \in \mathbb{R}^{m \times k}] and stem:[B \in \mathbb{R}^{k \times n}], their product stem:[C = AB \in \mathbb{R}^{m \times n}] is:

stem:[C_{ij} = \sum_{r=1}^{k} A_{ir} B_{rj}]

Each entry stem:[C_{ij}] is the dot product of row stem:[i] of stem:[A] with column stem:[j] of stem:[B].

In GPT, almost every computation is a matrix multiplication:
the embedding lookup, the query/key/value projections (Chapter 6), the feed-forward layers (Chapter 8), and the final vocabulary projection (Chapter 10).

==== Python Implementation

Matrices are represented as lists of row-lists.

[source,python]
----
include::../../../src/python/common.py[tag=matrix_ops]
----

In Python, `range(n)` produces the index sequence `0, 1, ..., n-1`.

==== Example

Let stem:[A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 \\ 3 & 4 \end{bmatrix}] and stem:[B = \begin{bmatrix} 5 & 6 \\ 7 & 8 \end{bmatrix}]:

stem:[C_{00} = 1 \cdot 5 + 2 \cdot 7 = 19]
stem:[C_{01} = 1 \cdot 6 + 2 \cdot 8 = 22]
stem:[C_{10} = 3 \cdot 5 + 4 \cdot 7 = 43]
stem:[C_{11} = 3 \cdot 6 + 4 \cdot 8 = 50]

So stem:[AB = \begin{bmatrix} 19 & 22 \\ 43 & 50 \end{bmatrix}].

